OSError: [Errno 36] File name too long: '# Oracle Cloud Infrastructure - Application Validation\n\n**ISV:** None  \n**Application:** None  \n**Statement of Work**  \n**Date:** None  \n**Version:** None\n\n---\n\n## Disclaimer\n\n This document, in any form, software or printed matter, contains proprietary information that is the exclusive property of Oracle. Your access to and use of this confidential material is subject to the terms and conditions of the Non-Disclosure Agreement between RedThorn and Oracle Corp. This document and information contained herein may not be disclosed, copied, reproduced, or distributed to anyone outside Oracle without prior written consent of Oracle. This document is not part of your license or services agreement nor can it be incorporated into any contractual agreement with Oracle or its subsidiaries or affiliates.\nThis document is for informational purposes only and is intended solely to assist you in evaluating the Oracle IaaS and/or Paas Public Cloud Services in a non-production context. It is not a commitment to deliver any material, code, or functionality, and should not be relied upon in making purchasing decisions. The development, release, and timing of any features or functionality described for Oracle products and services  remains at the sole discretion of Oracle.\nThe outcome of Oracle ISV Labs is to enable Redthorn OCI as outlined in this SOW, including any open source-based terraforms and tools/procedures, and it would be available to RedThorn to use freely with no restrictions or time limits and regardless of any NDA obligations.\n\n\n---\n\n## Contents\n1. [Version History](#version-history)\n2. [Current Status and Next Steps](#current-status-and-next-steps)\n3. [Project Participants](#project-participants)\n4. [Project Summary](#project-summary)\n5. [Current Architecture](#current-architecture)\n6. [Target Architecture](#target-architecture)\n7. [Implementation Details](#implementation-details)\n8. [Closing Remarks](#closing-remarks)\n\n---\n\n\n## Introduction\n\n\n# 1. Document Header\n- ISV: **dd**\n- Application: **OCI Application Validation**\n- Type: **Statement of Work**\n- Date: **2024-09-16**\n- Version: **0.1**\n- This document is confidential and contains proprietary information of Oracle Corporation. It is being provided to you solely for the purpose of facilitating your participation in the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) Application Validation project. By accepting this document, you agree to keep its contents confidential and not disclose them to any third party without the prior written consent of Oracle.\n\n\n# 2. SoW Version History Table\n| Version # | Date       | Revised By | Description of Change                                |\n|----------|------------|------------|------------------------------------------------------|\n| 0.1      | 2024-09-16 | Initial    | Initial version of the Statement of Work document    |\n\n\n# 3. Status and NEXT STEPS\n- Current project status: *Planning*\n- Next 3 actions required:\n  1. **Owner: Oracle Cloud Architect, Description:** Schedule a kickoff meeting with dd to discuss project objectives and timelines.\n  2. **Owner: dd Technical Lead, Description:** Provide Oracle with access to the dev/test environment for the ddd application.\n  3. **Owner: Oracle Cloud Architect, Description:** Begin designing the target OCI architecture for the ddd application.\n\n\n# 4. Project Participants Table\n\n\n Oracle Team\n| Name           | Role                 | Email                |\n|----------------|----------------------|----------------------|\n| John Doe       | Cloud Architect      | johndoe@oracle.com   |\n| Jane Smith     | Solutions Engineer   | janesmith@oracle.com |\n\n\n\n Client (dd) Team\n| Name           | Role                 | Email                |\n|----------------|----------------------|----------------------|\n| Michael Brown  | Technical Lead       | michaelbrown@dd.com  |\n| Emily Davis    | Project Manager      | emilydavis@dd.com    |\n\n\n# 5. Project Framework\nThe collaboration mode between Oracle and dd will involve regular meetings and feedback loops to ensure that the project objectives are met. Oracle will be responsible for designing and implementing the target OCI architecture, while dd will provide technical resources and access to the dev/test environment. The expected validation duration is approximately 2-3 weeks.\n\n\n# 6. Required Contribution From Client\ndd must provide the following:\n- Technical resources, including a dedicated technical lead and access to the dev/test environment.\n- Diagrams or architectural artifacts of the current ddd application setup.\n- Access to the dev/test environment for Oracle to conduct the validation.\n\n\n# 7. Expected Deliverables From Oracle ISV Labs\nThe expected deliverables from Oracle include:\n- Terraform modules for automating the deployment of the ddd application on OCI.\n- A detailed target architecture document outlining the recommended OCI services and configuration.\n- Technical documentation, including setup guides and troubleshooting tips.\n- CI/CD integration examples using Oracle Cloud DevOps services.\n\n\n# 8. Cloud Environment Used\nThe PoC will run in a temporary test tenancy provided by Oracle.\n\n\n# 9. dd Company Profile\n- Legal Name: **dd Corporation**\n- Country of Operations: **United States**\n- Company Overview: **dd is a leading provider of innovative software solutions.**\n- Website link: **https://www.dd.com**\n\n\n# 10. In-Scope Application: ddd\n- Application Name: **ddd**\n- General Description: **A cloud-native application for data processing and analytics.**\n- Key Technologies: **Kubernetes, PostgreSQL, Java**\n- Current Hosting: **On-prem**\n\n\n# 11. Project Overview\n- **Validation Summary:** The objective of this project is to validate the ddd application on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI).\n- Desired outcome:\n  - Successful deployment of the ddd application on OCI.\n  - Improved scalability and performance.\n  - Enhanced security and compliance.\n- Scope boundaries:\n  - The validation will focus on the ddd application only.\n  - The scope does not include production migration or licensing setup.\n- Joint goals:\n  - To demonstrate the feasibility of running the ddd application on OCI.\n  - To identify potential areas for optimization and improvement.\n\n\n# 12. Scope\n- **In-Scope Items:**\n  - PostgreSQL setup and configuration.\n  - Kubernetes deployment and management using OKE.\n  - Java application deployment and testing.\n- **Out-of-Scope Items:**\n  - Production migration and licensing setup.\n  - SLA support and ongoing maintenance.\n- Validation boundaries and limitations:\n  - The validation will be conducted in a temporary test tenancy.\n  - The scope of the validation is limited to the ddd application only.\n\n\n# 13. Major Project Milestones\n| Milestone                         | Target Date | Completed | Comments                 |\n|----------------------------------|-------------|-----------|--------------------------|\n| Kickoff with Cloud Architect     | 2024-09-17  |           |                          |\n| OCI Network Setup                | 2024-09-19  |           |                          |\n| Terraform Code Finalization      | 2024-09-22  |           |                          |\n| Application Deployment in OCI    | 2024-09-24  |           |                          |\n| Final Validation & Review        | 2024-09-26  |           |                          |\n\n\n# 14. Acceptance Criteria\n| Capability/Metric                                | Acceptance Criteria                                                       | Status  |\n|--------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------|\n| Kubernetes Deployment                            | ddd runs successfully on OCI OKE                 | TBD     |\n| OCI Streaming                                     | Kafka integration tested using OSS workloads                              | TBD     |\n| PostgreSQL                                        | DB deployed, configured, accessible                                       | TBD     |\n| Monitoring                                        | Basic metrics visible in OCI Monitoring dashboard                         | TBD     |\n| Security                                          | IAM + NSG + Encryption in Transit & At Rest                               | TBD     |\n\n\n# 15. Current State Architecture\n- **Diagram Description:** The current setup consists of on-premises Kubernetes clusters, PostgreSQL databases, and Java applications.\n- **Tech Stack:** Docker, Helm, PostgreSQL, Java, etc.\n- **Known Issues/Pain Points:** Manual deployments, scaling issues, and limited monitoring capabilities.\n\n\n# 16. Target OCI Architecture\nThe target OCI architecture will utilize the following services:\n- **OCI Compute:** For deploying and managing Kubernetes clusters.\n- **OCI Database:** For deploying and managing PostgreSQL databases.\n- **OCI Streaming:** For integrating Kafka with the ddd application.\n- **OCI Monitoring:** For monitoring and logging application metrics.\n- **Service Mapping:**\n  | Current Component | Target OCI Service |\n  |-------------------|--------------------|\n  | Kubernetes        | OKE                |\n  | PostgreSQL        | OCI Database       |\n  | Java Application  | OCI Compute        |\n- **Component Interaction:** The Kubernetes clusters will deploy and manage the Java applications, which will interact with the PostgreSQL databases using OCI Streaming.\n- **Diagram Placeholder:** A high-level architecture diagram will be provided, showing the interaction between the OCI services and the ddd application.\n\n\n# 17. Implementation Details and Configuration Settings\n- **Provisioning Shape/Config:** The provisioning shape and configuration will be determined based on the requirements of the ddd application.\n- **IAM Policies or NSGs Applied:** IAM policies and NSGs will be applied to ensure secure access to the OCI resources.\n- **Helm/Terraform Usage:** Helm and Terraform will be used to automate the deployment and management of the OCI resources.\n- **OKE Node Pools Config:** The OKE node pools will be configured to ensure high availability and scalability.\n- **PostgreSQL Shape, Version:** The PostgreSQL shape and version will be determined based on the requirements of the ddd application.\n- **Streaming Configuration:** The streaming configuration will be set up to integrate Kafka with the ddd application.\n- **Object Storage for Backups or Helm Registry:** Object storage will be used for backups and as a Helm registry.\n\n\n# 18. Security Considerations\n- **IAM Policy Examples:** IAM policies will be created to ensure secure access to the OCI resources.\n- **NSG Configuration:** NSGs will be configured to control traffic flow between the OCI resources.\n- **Data Encryption Approach:** Data encryption will be used to protect data in transit and at rest.\n- **Audit Logs or Logging Analytics Setup:** Audit logs and logging analytics will be set up to monitor and log application metrics.\n\n\n# 19. High Availability & Disaster Recovery\n- **OKE NodePools across ADs:** OKE node pools will be configured across multiple availability domains to ensure high availability.\n- **PostgreSQL HA with Replica:** PostgreSQL high availability will be configured with a replica to ensure data redundancy.\n- **Object Storage Cross-Region Replication:** Object storage cross-region replication will be set up to ensure data durability.\n- **DNS Failover via Traffic Management:** DNS failover will be configured using traffic management to ensure high availability.\n- **DR Architecture Summary:** A disaster recovery architecture summary will be provided, outlining the steps to be taken in case of a disaster.\n\n\n# 20. Closing Feedback\n- **Oracle:** The Oracle team will provide feedback on the project outcomes and suggest areas for improvement.\n- **dd:** The dd team will provide feedback on the project outcomes and suggest areas for improvement.\n\n\n# 21. Sign-Off Section\n- **Client Acceptance:** The client accepts the project outcomes and deliverables.\n- **Oracle Confirmation:** Oracle confirms that the project has been completed to the best of their abilities.\n- **Final Next Steps:** The final next steps will be outlined, including any additional work or follow-up activities.\n- **Version Tagging:** The final version of the document will be tagged and stored for future reference.\n---\n\n'
